@Søren Thustrup - regular old English.

Neaten = to make neat
in the same way straighten is to make straight, straiten is to make narrow, strengthen, whiten, hasten, quicken, etc.
The Danish ergative suffix is -ne, exactly cognate with English -en, btw. Højne, gulne, mildne, blåne…

“Unmet needs” is a totally normal way of saying “needs that have not yet been met (=fulfilled). Unmet demands, unmet quotas, unmet conditions. Normal English, though it requires the specific sense of “meet/met” that is “fitting/fulfilling/appropriate” rather than “encountering.”

Yell to is less usual, but would mean something different from yell at or just yell.
Yell - cry out loudly, as a personal emotive expression;
yell at - bellow at a person, berate, upbraid;
yell to - call out loudly to someone else as an act of communication. The clue indicated this correctly.

